    "summary": "The Establishment of Confucianism as State Ideology (136 BC) under [[event:1127|Emperor Wu of Han]] made Confucian texts the basis of government education and official recruitment, a decision that would shape Chinese civilization for over two millennia — making Confucianism not merely a philosophical school but the ideological foundation of the imperial state.\n\nEmperor Wu accepted the advice of his scholar-official Dong Zhongshu, who argued that Confucianism provided the best framework for harmonious government through its emphasis on hierarchical relationships, ritual propriety, and moral cultivation. The emperor established a Grand Academy (Taixue) where students mastered the Five Classics — the core Confucian texts — and officials began to be recruited on the basis of this learning. This created an examination-based bureaucracy whose members shared a common intellectual formation. The immediate impact was the displacement of other philosophical schools, especially [[event:1113|Legalism]], from official favor, though practical governance remained eclectic. The long-term impact was the creation of a scholar-gentry class that would serve as China's administrative elite for most of the next two thousand years, bound together by shared mastery of the Confucian canon.",
